PCA of Training Set

In this demo, we perform PCA on a dataset that relates measurements of fetal movements, collected during Cardiotocogram exams, with fetal health. This dataset is adapted from the one obtained in this paper: -Ayres de Campos et al.(2000) SisPorto 2.0 A Program for Automated Analysis of Cardiotocograms. J Matern Fetal Med 5:311-318

First lets take a look at our dataset

data = read.csv("data_train.csv")

We can get an idea of how correlated this variables are to start using a correlation matrix (like we did in the ggplot demo)

cor = cor(data %>% 
            select(-Stress_level))
Error in cor(data %>% select(-Stress_level)) : 'x' must be numeric

When performing PCA, it is important to standardize the variables to have mean zero and standard deviation one. Lets see how our unscaled and scaled data will differ during PCA.

ivs = data %>% select(-Stress_level, -sID)
pr_unscale = prcomp(ivs)
pr_scale = prcomp(ivs, scale=TRUE) # Note: output is a list, not a dataframe
# scale argument centers and scales

prcomp() provides us with a values:

names(pr_scale)
[1] "sdev"     "rotation" "center"   "scale"    "x"

Recall that the purpose of PCA is to create new, orthogonal features which are linear combinations of the original features with the goal of maximizing variance. We can visually how much of this variance is explained using a scree plot (Well use the factoextra package to make ours)

fviz_eig(pr_scale, addlabels = T, ncp = 16)

fviz_eig(pr_unscale, addlabels = T, ncp = 16) # Why does the first PC of our unscaled data describe so much more variance than in the scaled data? Features with larger values appear to contribute more to the variance within the data compared to the smaller valued features when unscaled.

We can also looks at these in tabular form

get_eig(pr_scale)

We can also visualize our first two PCs (which explain 54% of our cumulative variance) using a biplot. If you wished to visualize the first 3 principal components, you could create a 3D visualization with the plotly package.

To create our biplot, well use the factoextra package

fviz_pca_biplot(pr_scale)

If we know our class labels, we can actually take this visualization one step further

fviz_pca_biplot(pr_scale, habillage = data$Stress_level)

We can also visualize this data without the PCs

# Easier data visualization using factoextra
fviz_pca_biplot(pr_scale,
             col.ind = 'coord',
             habillage = data$Stress_level, label = "var", title = "PCA Biplot of Across Stress Levels in Training Data")
